The key steps are as follows: 1. **Reflecting the point across three sides**: - Reflecting the point \((2/7, 3/7)\) across the left side (x=0) results in \((-2/7, 3/7)\). - Reflecting this result across the top side (y=1) results in \((-2/7, 4/7)\). - Reflecting this result across the right side (x=1) results in \((9/7, 4/7)\). 2. **Calculating the distance**: - The straight-line distance from the original point \((2/7, 3/7)\) to the final reflected point \((9/7, 4/7)\) is calculated using the distance formula: \[ \text{Distance} = \sqrt{\left(\frac{9}{7} - \frac{2}{7}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{4}{7} - \frac{3}{7}\right)^2} = \sqrt{\left(\frac{7}{7}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{7}\right)^2} = \sqrt{1 + \frac{1}{49}} = \sqrt{\frac{50}{49}} = \frac{5\sqrt{2}}{7} \] Thus, the shortest path that touches three sides of the square and returns to the original point has a length of \(\boxed{\dfrac{5\sqrt{2}}{7}}\).
